{
  "texts": [
    "Nandhini and Karthikeyan [93] reported that using pulverized eggshell powder (PES) reduced water penetration by 50%, indicating a substantial improvement in the concrete's impermeability and resistance to environmental degradation.",
    "Similarly, Jaber et al. [95] found that treated eggshell powder (TESP) reduced water absorption by 30% at a 15% replacement level, reflecting its ability to refine the pore structure and lower permeability, which is crucial for enhancing the concrete's long-term durability.",
    "Maqsood and Eddie [94] demonstrated that calcined eggshell powder (CESP) increased electrical resistance by 90% at both 10% and 20% replacement levels, indicating reduced ion mobility and lower permeability, which are vital for preventing the ingress of harmful substances such as chlorides and sulfates.",
    "Shiferaw et al. [96] also confirmed the durability benefits of ESP, showing a 30% reduction in water absorption at a 15% replacement level, ReviewDiscover Civil Engineering (2024) 1:145 | https://doi.org/10.1007/s44290-024-00154-z further highlighting its capacity to limit moisture ingress and enhance the material's resistance to freeze-thaw cycles and chemical attack.",
    "Ibrahim and Meawad [97] found that adding soda-lime glass powder at 10%, 15%, and 20% by weight effectively reduces alkali silica reaction (ASR) expansion, thereby enhancing concrete's resistance to chemical attacks due to the glass powder's pozzolanic activity."
  ]
}